}
}
}
{\b0 \cf22 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa400 \sb400 
 the renewal by consent of a tenancy which, by express terms of the contract creating it, expired on a specified date. We conclude that the trial court did not err in admitting testimony of the making of the oral demand for possession by respondents.\u8217\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf22 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf22 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf22 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf22 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf22 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
If an oral demand for possession is sufficient before the expiration of a yearly lease, clearly the notice given in this case was sufficient for the same purpose. We are of the opinion, therefore, that the first notice was sufficient upon which to base the action for unlawful detainer. We are also of the opinion that the giving of the subsequent notices did not amount to a waiver of the first notice.
\par 
}
}
